  • Boutikos potamos
    An ancient canal of the Egyptian delta, with its western end on the Canopic branch of the Nile at Hierakonpolis and its eastern end at Pelusium (modern Tell el-Farama), deviating from an east-west line between the two at Bouto (modern Kom el-Farain).
    Creators: A. Bernand
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker

  • Chersonnesos Akra
    In describing features on the Red Sea coast of Arabia Felix, Ptolemy lists the Chesonnesos Akra. In the Barrington Atlas directory for Map 83, Graf suggests the Ras Abu Madd peninsula as a likely identification, but on the corresponding map, he labels a different feature: the mountainous Jabal Ral outcropping, about 120km north of Ras Abu Madd and some 40km east of the modern coastline.
    Creators: D.F. Graf
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker

  • Untitled
    Unnamed route or road
    Creators: S.M. Burstein
    Contributors: D. Borough, R. Talbert, Tom Elliott, Sean Gillies
  • Velini L.
    In the Roman period the Lacus Velinus was a larger body of water than the surviving remnant that is now known as Lake Piediluco. Modern intervention drained water away from the lake into the lower Nera River.
    Creators: W.V. Harris
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Velini (lake)
    A lake formed by three rivers (Avens, Himella and Tolenus) in the territory of the Sabines.
    Creators: W.V. Harris
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Vesulus (mountain)
    Monte Viso is the highest peak of the Cottian Alps and the source of the Po river.
    Creators: E. Bertrand
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Appia
    An early Roman road (via publica) originating at Rome and terminating at Brundisium, the Via Appia was begun in the fourth century B.C. by the censor Appius Claudius Caecus. The Latin author Statius described the Via Appia as "queen of the long roads".
    Creators: L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Ardeatina
    The Via Ardeatina connected Rome and Ardea.
    Creators: L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Aurelia
    A Roman road.
    Creators: S. Loseby
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Aurelia
    An ancient Roman road begun ca. 241 B.C. by the censor C. Aurelius Cotta.
    Creators: L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Campana?
    A road located on the right bank of the Tiber leading to the Campus Salinarum romanarum and sharing the first part of its course with the Via Portuensis.
    Creators: L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Cassia
    An ancient Roman road branching off from the Via Flaminia and continuing to Luna where it joined the Via Aurelia. The Via Cassia post-dates the Via Amerina and was built after 240 B.C. It combined new construction with re-use of pre-existing roads and tracks.
    Creators: L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Clodia
    An ancient Roman road.
    Creators: L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Collatina
    A Roman road connecting Rome with Collatia.
    Creators: L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Cornelia
    The Via Cornelia was an ancient road that ran along the north side of the circus Gai et Neronis. The road diverged from the Via Triumphalis west of the pons Neronianus, near a large tomb known as the Meta Romuli.
    Creators: L. Quilici, S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Domitia
    The Via Domitia connected Italia and Hispania and was built ca. 118 BC by Cnaeus Domitius Ahenobarbus around the time Colonia Narbo Martius (Narbonne) was founded.
    Creators: S. Loseby
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Labicana
    An ancient Roman road connecting Rome and Labicum.
    Creators: L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Latina
    A Roman road running southeast from Rome toward Campania.
    Creators: L. Quilici, S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Laurentina
    An ancient road, leading southwards from Rome toward Laurentum. Its course, endpoint, and coincidence with the Via Ostiensis and the Via Ardeatina are matters of scholarly contention.
    Creators: L. Quilici, S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Nomentana
    The ancient road connecting Rome and Nomentum.
    Creators: L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Ostiensis
    An ancient road running from Rome to Ostia, exiting the city walls of Rome at the Porta Trigemina.
    Creators: L. Quilici, S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Portuensis?
    The Via Portuensis is an ancient Roman road that connected Rome and Portus. It proceeded along the right bank of the Tiber river, starting from the Pons Aemilius. In the first part of its course it is identical to the Via Campana.
    Creators: L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Praenestina
    A consular road running from Rome to Praeneste.
    Creators: L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Salaria
    An ancient road that originated at Rome and continued to Castrum Truentinum (Porto d'Ascoli).
    Creators: L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Sebaste: Apollonia ↔ Antiochia ↔ Neapolis
    A road network in Pisidia originally built by the governor Cornutus Aquila, beginning ca. 6 BC.
    Creators: T. Drew-Bear
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Severiana
    The Via Severiana was a coastal route running from Ostia to Terracina, a distance of ca. 80 Roman miles.
    Creators: L. Quilici, S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Sublacensis
    The Via Sublacensis was built in order to connect the Villa Neronis (Nero's villa at Sublaqueum) to Rome. It split from the Via Valeria near Varia.
    Creators: L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Tiburtina
    An ancient road heading east-northeast from Rome to Tibur.
    Creators: L. Quilici, S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Triumphalis
    A road running from the Pons Neronianus toward Monte Mario, eventually joining the Via Clodia some 7 miles from Rome.
    Creators: L. Quilici, S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Via Valeria
    An ancient road from Rome to Corfinium.
    Creators: L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Xanthos (river)
    An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C2 Xanthos fl.
    Creators: C. Foss, G. Reger, S. Mitchell
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott
  • Xynias L.
    Xynias L. (Lake Xynias) occupied an extinct caldera in antiquity, but has since dried up.
    Creators: J. Fossey, J. Morin
    Contributors: R. Talbert, G. Reger, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Zagatis (river)
    An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 F3 Zagatis fl.
    Creators: T. Sinclair, David Braund
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Diane Braund, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott
  • Zaigaina (islands)
    Mentioned by Ptolemy, the Zaigaina "islands" are identified by modern scholars with the so-called Daedalus reef in the Red Sea.
    Creators: D.F. Graf
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • Zalekos (river)
    An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 A3 Zalekos fl.
    Creators: T. Sinclair, David Braund
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Diane Braund, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
  • (Z)Apaortenon? M.
    An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 97 E3 (Z)Apaortenon? M.
    Creators: E.J. Keall, M. Roaf
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Tom Elliott, Sean Gillies
  • Zephyrion Pr.
    An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 74 C2 Zephyrion Pr.
    Creators: A. Bernand
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Tom Elliott, Sean Gillies
  • Zephyrion Pr.
    An ancient place, cited: None

  • Zephyrios Pr.

  • Zered (river)

  • Zouchis L.

  • Albanus L.

  • Albanus M.
    The second highest summit of the Alban Hills, Mons Albanus is an extinct volcano with an elevation of 950 m (3,117 ft). In the middle of the first millennium B.C. there may have been volcanic activity as noted by the historian Livy. The mountain was sacred for Latin peoples who held important festivals there and a major shrine to Iuppiter Latiaris stands on the mountain top.
    Creators: L. Quilici, S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Johan Åhlfeldt, John Muccigrosso, Jeffrey Becker, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott

  • Alsietinus lacus
    The Alsietinus lacus, modern Lago di Martignano, is a small volcanic crater-lake in southern Etruria. The lake was the source of the Augustan aqueduct aqua Augusta Alsietina that served non-potable water to the Transtiberim and Ianiculum.

  • Apesas (mountain)
    Mount Aphesas, now Mount Phoukas, separated the terriroty of Kleonai from the Corinthia. It is connected with the myth of the Nemean lion and was the site of an ash altar sacred to Zeus in use from the Geometric period to the fourth century B.C.
    Creators: G. Reger, J. McK. Camp II

  • Aphrodisias

  • Arachnaion (mountain)
    A mountain of the Argolid with a higher western peak (Profitis Ilias, 1199 masl) and a lower eastern peak (Mavrovouni or Arna, 1139 masl). Material from the Mycenaean, Archaic, and Classical periods has been found on the western peak and identified with altars of Zeus and Hera described by Pausanias. Aeschylus mentions its use as a signal station.
    Creators: G. Reger, J. McK. Camp II
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Dan Diffendale, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
    Modifications: finding mountains by their titles and setting feature types

  • Cephisis
    An ancient body of water, mentioned by Skylax and Pliny the Elder (who terms it a "lacus") bordering the Atlantic coast in what is now northwest Morocco. Some modern scholars believe it should be associated with the modern Oued Tahadart/Oued Khobs near El Khaoucha.
    Creators: M. Euzennat

  • Hypios (river)
    A river mentioned in ancient sources. Modern scholars identify it with the lower/larger (Büyük) course of the modern Melen Çay (Buyukmelen), which drains the marshy Efteni Golü (much diminished from its pre-modern extent). Ancient people seem to have extended the "Hypios" name past the lake and up one of its tributaries, but scholarly opinion is divided as to whether this was the modern Ugursuyu/Ogursu/Akarsu (Robert 1980, whence Foss in BAtlas) or the upper/smaller (Küçük) Melen Çayı (Strobel in New Pauly).
    Creators: C. Foss
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
    Modifications: finding rivers by their titles and setting feature types
    Actors: Sean Gillies

  • Korax (mountain)
    An ancient mountain of Aetolia, known today as Giona. Some ancient sources, echoed or interpreted by modern commentators, seem also to include or alternately identify the nearby mountain known today as Vardousia, although most recent scholarship rejects this notion. A peak of Vardousia (Βαρδούσια) seems to have acquired variants of the name "Korax" in modern times.
    Creators: J. Fossey, J. Morin
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Brady Kiesling, Sean Gillies, Jeffrey Becker, G. Reger, Tom Elliott
    Modifications: finding mountains by their titles and setting feature types
    Actors: Sean Gillies
